It is observable that in this ode as well as in the last, and in Odes v. and vi., composed for political purposes, Horace indulges much more in the flights and fancies and seeming digressions proper to poetry purely lyrical than in Odes i. and ii„ in which, inculcating moral or noble sentiments applicable to men of all parties, he is earnestly didactic. But treating political subjects‚ on which men’s minds were divided‚ he shows wonderful delicacy of art in conveying his purpose through forms of poetry least likely to offend.
